'''Julio César Enciso Espínola''' (born 23 January 2004) is a Paraguayan professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as an [[attacking midfielder]] or [[left winger]] for {{French football updater|Strasbourg}} club [[RC Strasbourg Alsace|Strasbourg]] and the [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguay national team]].

==Club career==
===Early career===
Enciso started playing football at his local club in [[Caaguazú, Paraguay|Caaguazú]], Paraguay. At age 12 he was recruited by [[Club Libertad|Libertad]].<ref name=WFS>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldfootballscouting.com/schede-giovani-talenti/julio-enciso-talento-paraguayano-classe-2004/|title=Julio Enciso: talento paraguayano classe 2004|date=18 December 2019|website=World football scouting|language=it}}</ref> Enciso made his senior debut for Club Libertad on 17 March 2019, aged 15, in a 4–0 home victory against [[Deportivo Santaní]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2019/03/17/paraguay/division-profesional/club-libertad/deportivo-santani/2949445/|title=Libertad vs. Deportivo Santaní – 17 March 2019 – Soccerway|publisher=Soccerway|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> He became the youngest player to debut with Libertad.<ref name="WFS" />

===Brighton and Hove Albion===
On 17 June 2022, Enciso transferred to [[Premier League]] club [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] for a transfer fee of £9.5&nbsp;million plus future add-on fees, signing an initial four-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2647985/julio-enciso-signs-for-albion|title=Julio Enciso signs for Albion|date=17 June 2022|publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|access-date=17 June 2022|archive-date=19 June 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220619100429/https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2647985/julio-enciso-signs-for-albion|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3490107/2022/06/13/brighton-complete-signing-of-paraguay-international-julio-enciso/|title= Brighton complete signing of Paraguay international Julio Enciso|date=17 June 2022|work=The Athletic|access-date=17 June 2022}}</ref> He made his Brighton debut on 24 August, playing 80 minutes of the 3–0 away win over [[EFL League One|League One]] side [[Forest Green Rovers F.C.|Forest Green Rovers]] in the [[2022–23 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] second round, where he claimed assist to [[Steven Alzate]]'s long range goal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62571845|title=Forest Green 0–3 Brighton: Albion to face Arsenal in third round |publisher=BBC Sport|date=24 August 2022|access-date=2 September 2022}}</ref>

Enciso made his [[Premier League]] debut on 29 October, coming on as a 65th minute substitute for [[Adam Lallana]] in Brighton's 4–1 home win over [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.premierleague.com/match/75044 |title=Brighton v Chelsea 2022/23|publisher=Premier League Sport|date=29 October 2022|access-date=29 October 2022}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club on 4 April 2023, in a 2–0 away win at [[AFC Bournemouth|Bournemouth]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Bournemouth 0–2 Brighton & Hove Albion: Evan Ferguson flick boosts Seagulls' top-four hopes|work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/62776440 |date=4 April 2023|access-date=4 April 2023}}</ref> Nearly two weeks later, he scored in a 1–2 away win over Chelsea, helping the Albion secure a victory at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] for the first time in their history.<ref>{{Cite news |date=15 April 2023 |title=Enciso stunner gives Brighton victory at Chelsea |language=en-GB |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/65217807 |access-date=15 April 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=15 April 2023 |title=Chelsea 1–2 Brighton: Julio Enciso fires superb winner to boost Seagulls' European dreams with historic win at Stamford Bridge |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/12309/12855741/chelsea-1-2-brighton-julio-enciso-fires-superb-winner-to-boost-seagulls-european-dreams-with-historic-win-at-stamford-bridge |access-date=15 April 2023 |website=Sky Sports |language=en}}</ref>

Enciso started in the [[2022–23 FA Cup|FA Cup]] semi-final at [[Wembley Stadium|Wembley]] on 23 April, playing 67 minutes as Brighton eventually lost 7–6 on penalties to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3231077/its-wembley-heartbreak-as-albion-are-beaten-on-penalties|title=It's Wembley heartbreak as Albion are beaten on penalties|website=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|date=23 April 2023|access-date=24 April 2023|archive-date=19 January 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240119172402/https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3231077/its-wembley-heartbreak-as-albion-are-beaten-on-penalties|url-status=dead}}</ref>
Three days later, the 19-year-old made his first Premier League start for the ''Albion,'' in the 3–1 away loss at [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3237654/albion-felled-by-forest|title=Albion felled by Forest|publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion|date=26 April 2023|access-date=26 April 2023|archive-date=26 April 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230426204036/https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3237654/albion-felled-by-forest/|url-status=dead}}</ref> Three days after that on 29 April, he made two assists in Brighton's 6–0 home victory over the [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolves]], Brighton's biggest Premier League victory.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3245199/back-on-track-with-six-of-the-best|title=Back on track with six of the best|publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion|date=29 April 2023|access-date=29 April 2023|archive-date=30 November 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231130133930/https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3245199/back-on-track-with-six-of-the-best|url-status=dead}}</ref>

On 14 May, Enciso opened the scoreline with a header from a [[Pervis Estupiñán]] cross in an eventual 3–0 away win at [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=It's three and easy as magnificent Albion move up to sixth|url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3345249/its-three-and-easy-as-magnificent-albion-move-up-to-sixth|date=14 May 2023|access-date=14 May 2023|website=Brighton & Hove Albion |language=en-GB}}</ref> He scored his first goal at [[Falmer Stadium]] on 24 May, scoring a 25-yard goal against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], with Brighton sealing a place in the [[2023–24 UEFA Europa League]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65290302|title=Brighton 1–1 Manchester City: Julio Enciso scores stunning equaliser to seal Europa League place|work=BBC Sport|date=24 May 2023|access-date=24 May 2023}}</ref> The goal was chosen as [[BBC]] [[BBC Goal of the Season|Goal of the Season]] for [[2022-23 in English football|2022–23]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Match of the Day on Twitter |url=https://twitter.com/BBCMOTD/status/1662960443537670146 |access-date=29 May 2023 |publisher=BBC}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=June 2025}} and later chosen as [[Premier League Goal of the Season]], beating out the likes of Brentford's [[Ivan Toney]] and Newcastle's [[Miguel Almirón]] in a vote decided by a panel of experts as well as the public's opinion.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |date=4 June 2023 |title=Enciso wins Budweiser Goal of the Season award |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/3527787 |publisher=Premier League}}</ref> Enciso also went on win the Goal of the Season at Brighton's end of season awards.<ref name="Awards">{{cite web|url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3613149/caicedo-is-double-award-winner|title=Caicedo is double award winner|website=Brighton & Hove Albion|date=2 August 2023|access-date=7 August 2023|archive-date=23 September 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230923114922/https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3613149/caicedo-is-double-award-winner|url-status=dead}}</ref>

On 19 August 2023, Enciso set up both of [[Solly March]]'s goals in a 4–1 away win at [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]], Brighton's second match of the [[2023–24 Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. season|2023–24 season]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Morgan |first=Richard |date=19 August 2023 |title=Wolves 1–4 Brighton: Solly March double helps visitors to easy Molineux win |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12941639/wolves-1-4-brighton-solly-march-double-helps-visitors-to-resounding-win |access-date=28 August 2023 |website=Sky Sports |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=20 August 2023 |title=March: De Zerbi has set me a target of 15 goals |publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion |url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3644608/march-de-zerbi-has-set-me-a-target-of-15-goals |access-date=21 August 2023}}</ref> However, the following week, the striker suffered a knee issue and was subsequently ruled out for "a long period", according to manager [[Roberto De Zerbi]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theargus.co.uk/sport/23748869.roberto-de-zerbis-message-injured-julio-enciso/|title=Roberto De Zerbi's message to injured Julio Enciso|work=The Argus|date=26 August 2023|access-date=26 August 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Smith |first=Adam |date=28 August 2023 |title=Brighton manager Roberto De Zerbi on Kaoru Mitoma and Solly March form, Julio Enciso injury and Evan Ferguson potential |url=https://www.skysports.com/transfer/news/11741/12945687/brighton-manager-roberto-de-zerbi-on-kaoru-mitoma-and-solly-march-form-julio-enciso-injury-and-evan-ferguson-potential |access-date=28 August 2023 |website=Sky Sports |language=en-GB}}</ref>

====Loan to Ipswich Town====
On 23 January 2025, Enciso joined fellow Premier League club [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] on loan for the remainder of the [[2024–25 Ipswich Town F.C. season|2024–25 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itfc.co.uk/news/2025/january/23/julio-enciso-joins-ipswich-town-on-loan/|title=JULIO ENCISO JOINS IPSWICH TOWN ON LOAN|publisher=Ipswich Town F.C.|date=23 January 2025|access-date=23 January 2025}}</ref> He made his debut against Liverpool in a 4–1 loss, coming on as a substitute.{{citation needed|date=August 2025}}

===Strasbourg===
On 1 September 2025, Enciso joined [[Ligue 1]] club [[RC Strasbourg|Strasbourg]] on a deal worth £17 million, with Brighton retaining a sell-on clause.

==International career==
Enciso is a Paraguayan youth international, having played with the Paraguay U15 side at the [[2019 South American U-15 Championship]].<ref name=WFS/> He first represented the senior [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguay national team]] in a 3–1 [[2021 Copa América]] win over [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia]] on 14 June 2021.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2021/06/15/south-america/copa-america/paraguay/bolivia/3189335/ | title=Paraguay vs. Bolivia – 15 June 2021 – Soccerway }}</ref>

== Player profile ==
{{blockquote|“Julio [Enciso] is a highly talented footballer. His speed, energy and ability to break lines are qualities that we need.”|[[Liam Rosenior]], Enciso's manager at [[Racing Strasbourg]] (23 October 2025).<ref name=futboleros>{{Cite web|url=https://futboleros.com.py/julio-enciso-debuta-en-europa-con-el-estrasburgo-y-participa-en-un-empate-vibrante-ante-el-jagiellonia-por-la-conference-league|title=Julio Enciso makes his European debut with Strasbourg and features in a thrilling draw against Jagiellonia in the Conference League|website=Futboleros NET|date=23 October 2025|access-date=20 April 2026|language=es}}</ref>}}
Enciso plays as a [[central forward]] and is [[right-footed]]. Agile in his movements, with a good sense of goal, a precise shot from mid-range, and skill in [[dribbling]].<ref name="str">{{cite web |url=https://strikers.futbol/fichajes/Quien-es-Julio-Enciso-la-estrella-del-futbol-de-Paraguay-que-pretenden-varios-grandes-de-Europa-20210416-0048.html |title=Quién es Julio Enciso, la estrella del fútbol de Paraguay que pretenden varios grandes de Europa |date=16 April 2021 |access-date=27 January 2025 |work=Strikers |language=es}}</ref><ref name="yb">{{cite news |url=https://www.infobae.com/america/agencias/2023/04/18/julio-enciso-el-canon-del-brighton |title=Julio Enciso, el cañón del Brighton |last=Sánchez Gómez |first=Manuel |date=18 April 2023 |access-date=27 January 2025 |work=[[Infobae]] |language=es}}</ref> In addition to his main position as a central forward, he can also play on the wings as an attacker or in a more central role, such as an attacking [[midfielder]] or false 9.<ref name=WFS/><ref name=en>{{cite web |last=Edwards |first=Daniel |url=https://www.goal.com/it/notizie/julio-enciso-talento-paraguaiano-nxgn/blt597a5c27caa0b833 |title=Julio Enciso, il talento paraguaiano che interessa anche in Europa |work=Goal |date=11 January 2022 |access-date=27 January 2025 |language=it}}</ref><ref name="str"/> In an interview with ''[[Infobae]]'', Enciso expressed his willingness to occupy different positions within the team and his ability to adapt to the coach's requirements.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.infobae.com/america/agencias/2023/06/16/enciso-aspira-a-anotar-su-primer-gol-con-la-seleccion-de-paraguay-frente-a-nicaragua/ |title=Enciso aspira a anotar su primer gol con la selección de Paraguay frente a Nicaragua |date=16 June 2023 |access-date=27 January 2025 |work=Infobae |language=es}}</ref>

In another interview, Enciso mentioned that he drew inspiration from his compatriot [[Óscar Cardozo]], with whom he shared a team at [[Club Libertad]].<ref name=en/><ref name="ln">{{cite news |url=https://www.lanacion.com.py/futboledicion-impresa/2022/06/10/la-joya-se-despidio/ |title="La Joya" se despidió |date=10 June 2022 |access-date=27 January 2025 |work=La Nación |language=es}}</ref> He also spoke about his admiration for [[Ronaldinho]], whom he considers his idol, and his attentive observation of [[Cristiano Ronaldo]]’s plays.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.versus.com.py/versus/2022/06/14/enciso-confeso-quien-es-su-idolo-en-la-premier-league-y-esta-ansioso-por-enfrentarlo/ |title=Enciso confesó quién es su ídolo en la Premier League y está ansioso por enfrentarlo |date=14 June 2022 |access-date=27 January 2025 |work=Versus |language=es}}</ref>

In 2021, Enciso was included in the list of the top sixty footballers born in 2004, compiled by the British newspaper ''[[The Guardian]]''. In June 2023, he was nominated for the [[Golden Boy Award]], given annually by the Italian newspaper ''[[Tuttosport]]'', ranking 48th among the 100 candidates. Both Enciso and Argentine [[Alejandro Garnacho]] were the only South American representatives selected for this recognition.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hoy.com.py/deportes/julio-enciso-entre-los-primeros-50-candidatos-al-golden-boy |title=Julio Enciso entre los primeros 50 candidatos al Golden Boy |date=20 June 2023 |access-date=27 January 2025 |work=Hoy |language=es}}</ref>

On 17 July 2024, Enciso was recognised as the second-best U-21 player in the world in terms of creativity and effectiveness in finishing plays, second only to French player [[Rayan Cherki]]. This recognition comes from an analysis by the [[Centre International d'Etude du Sport]] (CIES) and was shared through [[Twitter|X]]. Enciso scored 78.7 out of 100, standing out for his ability to create goal-scoring opportunities and take shots on target, although the analysis did not evaluate the accuracy of his shots.<ref name=cies>{{cite news |url=https://www.versus.com.py/hoy/2024/07/23/un-paraguayo-entre-los-mejores-creativos-sub-21-del-mundo/ |title=Un paraguayo entre los mejores creativos sub-21 del mundo |date=23 July 2024 |work=Versus |access-date=27 January 2025 |language=es}}</ref>

